GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 528
Short Title: Child Care Regulatory Reforms & Flexibilities. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Burgin, Galey, and Corbin (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAKE VARIOUS CHILD CARE REGULATORY REFORMS AND PROVIDE
3 FOR FLEXIBILITIES IN SCHOOL-AGE CHILD CARE.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5
6 PART I. VARIOUS CHILD CARE REGULATORY REFORMS
7
8 EXPERIENCE EQUIVALENCY FOR LEAD TEACHERS IN LICENSED CHILD CARE
9 SECTION 1.1.(a) G.S. 110-90(4) reads as rewritten:
10 "(4) To issue a rated license to any child care facility which meets the standards
11 established by this Article as follows:
12 a. For any child care facility currently holding a license of two to five
13 stars or any new license issued to a child care facility with a rating of
14 two to five stars, the rating shall be based on (i) program standards and
15 (ii) education levels of staff. When evaluating program standards, the
16 Department shall consider the facility's staff/child ratios, space
17 requirements, continuous quality improvement standards, family and
18 community engagement practices, environmental rating scale
19 evaluations, curriculum, child observation and assessment, staff
20 coaching or mentoring, or accreditation by a national or regional
21 accrediting agency with early childhood standards. When evaluating
22 education levels of staff, the Department shall consider any early
23 childhood and child development coursework, early childhood
24 education certificates, Child Development Associate credentials,
25 associate or bachelor's degrees, continuous quality improvement
26 standards for staff, continuing education units, early childhood
27 education competency evaluations, work experience in child care,
28 including staff granted the North Carolina Early Childhood Credential
29 based on experience pursuant to G.S. 110-91, coaching or mentoring
30 completed, and education standards within an accreditation award.
31 …."
32 SECTION 1.1.(b) Section 8 of S.L. 2024-34 is amended by adding a new subsection
33 to read:
34 "SECTION 8.(a1) In modifying the quality rating improvement system (QRIS), the Division
35 of Child Development and Early Education shall ensure a North Carolina Early Childhood
36 Credential based on five years of work experience in a licensed child care facility in this State is
*S528-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 treated as equivalent to when that credential is earned through other pathways for purposes of
2 awarding a star rating."
3 SECTION 1.2. G.S. 110-91(8) reads as rewritten:
4 "(8) Qualifications for Staff. – Qualifications for child care staff are as follows:
5 a. All child care center administrators shall be at least 21 years of age.
6 All child care center administrators shall have the North Carolina
7 Early Childhood Administration Credential or its equivalent as
8 determined by the Department. All child care administrators
9 performing administrative duties as of the date this act becomes law
10 and child care administrators who assume administrative duties at any
11 time after this act becomes law and until September 1, 1998, shall
12 obtain the required credential by September 1, 2000. Child care
13 administrators who assume administrative duties after September 1,
14 1998, shall begin working toward the completion of the North Carolina
15 Early Childhood Administration Credential or its equivalent within six
16 months after assuming administrative duties and shall complete the
17 credential or its equivalent within two years after beginning work to
18 complete the credential. Each child care center shall be under the
19 direction or supervision of a person meeting these requirements. All
20 staff counted toward meeting the required staff-child ratio shall be at
21 least 16 years of age, provided that persons younger than 18 years of
22 age work under the direct supervision of a credentialed staff person
23 who is at least 21 years of age.
24 b. All lead teachers in a child care center shall have at least a North
25 Carolina Early Childhood Credential or its equivalent as determined
26 by the Department. Lead teachers shall either (i) be enrolled in the
27 North Carolina Early Childhood Credential coursework or its
28 equivalent as determined by the Department within six months after
29 becoming employed as a lead teacher or within six months after this
30 act becomes law, whichever is later, and shall complete the credential
31 or its equivalent within 18 months after enrollment.enrollment or (ii)
32 have a minimum of five years of documented experience teaching in a
33 licensed child care facility in this State which shall be deemed
34 equivalent to the North Carolina Early Childhood Credential.
35 c. For child care centers licensed to care for 200 or more children, the
36 Department, in collaboration with the North Carolina Institute for
37 Early Childhood Professional Development, shall establish categories
38 to recognize the levels of education achieved by child care center
39 administrators and teachers who perform administrative functions.
40 The Department shall use these categories to establish appropriate
41 staffing based on the size of the center and the individual staff
42 responsibilities.
43 d. Effective January 1, 1998, an operator of a licensed family child care
44 home shall be at least 21 years old and have a high school diploma or
45 its equivalent. Operators of a family child care home licensed prior to
46 January 1, 1998, shall be at least 18 years of age and literate. Literate
47 is defined as understanding licensing requirements and having the
48 ability to communicate with the family and relevant emergency
49 personnel. Any operator of a licensed family child care home shall be
50 the person on-site providing child care.
