1
2 CLARIFY RULES ON MULTIUSE CHILD CARE CENTERS
3 SECTION 1.4. The Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child
4 Development and Early Education (Division), in coordination with the Child Care Commission,
5 shall work to clarify the rules governing multiuse child care centers to ensure each of the
6 following:
7 (1) Allow the use of existing buildings to house multiunit child care centers and
8 include mixed-age centers if they meet the requirements outlined in the rules
9 regarding multiunit child care centers.
10 (2) Grant access to applicants who meet the pre-licensing guidelines and are
11 awarded a license by the Division.
12 (3) Grant individual licenses within a multiunit child care center based on the
13 square footage used by each owner.
14
15 PART II. SCHOOL-AGE FLEXIBILITIES
16 SECTION 2.1. G.S. 110-91(6) reads as rewritten:
17 "(6) Space and Equipment Requirements. – There shall be no less than 25 square
18 feet of indoor space for each child for which a child care center is licensed,
19 exclusive of closets, passageways, kitchens, and bathrooms, and this floor
20 space shall provide during rest periods 200 cubic feet of airspace per child for
21 which the center is licensed. There shall be adequate outdoor play area for
22 each child under rules adopted by the Commission which shall be related to
23 the size of center and the availability and location of outside land area. In no
24 event shall the minimum required exceed 75 square feet per child. The outdoor
25 area shall be protected to assure the safety of the children receiving child care
26 by an adequate fence or other protection. A center operated in a public school
27 shall be deemed to have adequate fencing protection. A center operating
28 exclusively during the evening and early morning hours, between 6:00 P.M.
29 and 6:00 A.M., need not meet the outdoor play area requirements mandated
30 by this subdivision.
31 Each child care facility shall provide indoor area equipment and
32 furnishings that are child size, sturdy, safe, and in good repair. Each child care
33 facility that provides outdoor area equipment and furnishings shall provide
34 outdoor area equipment and furnishings that are child size, sturdy, free of
35 hazards that pose a threat of serious injury to children while engaged in normal
36 play activities, and in good repair. The Commission shall adopt standards to
37 establish minimum requirements for equipment appropriate for the size of
38 child care facility. Space shall be available for proper storage of beds, cribs,
39 mats, cots, sleeping garments, and linens as well as designated space for each
40 child's personal belongings.
41 The Division of Child Development of the Department of Health and
42 Human Services shall establish and implement a policy that defines any
43 building which is currently approved for school occupancy and which houses
44 a public or private elementary or middle school to include the playgrounds
45 and athletic fields as part of the school building when that building is used to
46 serve school-age children in after-school out-of-school child care programs.
47 Playgrounds Except as provided in subdivision (6a) of this section,
48 playgrounds and athletic fields referenced in this section that do not meet
49 licensure standards promulgated by the North Carolina Child Care
50 Commission shall be noted on the program's licensure and rating
51 information."
Page 4 Senate Bill 528-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 2.2.(a) G.S. 110-91 is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
2 "(6a) Certain Exemptions for School-Age Children in Out-of-School Child Care. –
3 Notwithstanding any provision of law or rule to the contrary, any building and
4 grounds which are currently approved for school occupancy and which house
5 a public or private elementary or middle school shall be deemed to have met
6 the sanitation, fire, and building code requirements for a licensed child care
7 facility when the building and grounds are serving the same, or a subset of the
8 same, school-age children in an out-of-school child care program."
9 SECTION 2.2.(b) The Child Care Commission shall adopt or amend any rules to
10 ensure uniformity and consistency in application of the exemptions for school-age children in
11 out-of-school child care programs as provided in this section.
12 SECTION 2.3. G.S. 110-91(8) reads as rewritten:
13 "(8) Qualifications for Staff. – All child care center administrators shall be at least
14 21 years of age. All child care center administrators shall have the North
15 Carolina Early Childhood Administration Credential or its equivalent as
16 determined by the Department. Department or the School-Age Administration
17 Credential when providing school-age child care. All child care administrators
18 performing administrative duties as of the date this act becomes law and child
19 care administrators who assume administrative duties at any time after this act
20 becomes law and until September 1, 1998, shall obtain the required credential
21 by September 1, 2000. Child care administrators who assume administrative
22 duties after September 1, 1998, shall begin working toward the completion of
23 the North Carolina Early Childhood Administration Credential or its
24 equivalent equivalent, or the School-Age Administration Credential when
25 providing school-age child care, within six months after assuming
26 administrative duties and shall complete the credential or its equivalent within
27 two years after beginning work to complete the credential. Each child care
28 center shall be under the direction or supervision of a person meeting these
29 requirements. All staff counted toward meeting the required staff-child ratio
30 shall be at least 16 years of age, provided that persons younger than 18 years
31 of age work under the direct supervision of a credentialed staff person who is
32 at least 21 years of age. All lead teachers in a child care center shall have at
33 least a North Carolina Early Childhood Credential or its equivalent as
34 determined by the Department. Lead teachers shall be enrolled in the North
35 Carolina Early Childhood Credential coursework or its equivalent as
36 determined by the Department within six months after becoming employed as
37 a lead teacher or within six months after this act becomes law, whichever is
38 later, and shall complete the credential or its equivalent within 18 months after
39 enrollment.
40 For child care centers licensed to care for 200 or more children, the
41 Department, in collaboration with the North Carolina Institute for Early
42 Childhood Professional Development, shall establish categories to recognize
43 the levels of education achieved by child care center administrators and
44 teachers who perform administrative functions. The Department shall use
45 these categories to establish appropriate staffing based on the size of the center
46 and the individual staff responsibilities.
47 Effective January 1, 1998, an operator of a licensed family child care home
48 shall be at least 21 years old and have a high school diploma or its equivalent.
49 Operators of a family child care home licensed prior to January 1, 1998, shall
50 be at least 18 years of age and literate. Literate is defined as understanding
51 licensing requirements and having the ability to communicate with the family
